However, if the teams structured this trade as two separate trades - with the Hawks using a Traded Player Exception to acquire Hinrich, and the Bulls using the Minimum Player Salary Exception for Holiday - the Bulls would get a TPE for $2,854,940. I'll confirm this as soon as all the details of the trade are released. (<strong>EDIT</strong>: KC Johnson is reporting the TPE is for Hinrich's $2.8 million, but I am still waiting on independent confirmation)

The Bulls will also pick up a 2018 2nd-round draft pick from the Jazz (still not sure where they come in on the trade).<strong> EDIT</strong>: The Jazz get PG Shelvin Mack from the Hawks in the deal.

Holiday, 26, is a 6'6" shooting guard who went undrafted after graduating from the University of Washington in 2011. To date, his greatest NBA accomplishment is playing 59 games last season (including four starts) for the NBA Champion Golden State Warriors. He played only 11 minutes in the playoffs, but he did pick up a championship ring, so he has that going for him.

[caption id="attachment_2274" align="aligncenter" width="500"]<a href="http://www.chicagonow.com/bullsville/files/2016/02/ATL_Holiday_Justin.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-2274" alt="ATL_Holiday_Justin" src="http://www.chicagonow.com/bullsville/files/2016/02/ATL_Holiday_Justin.jpg" width="500" height="281" /></a> Justin Holiday[/caption]

He also won a few championships in Europe, meaning he has won three championships in his four professional seasons:
<ul>
	<li><span style="line-height: 13px;">Belgian Cup with <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Okapi_Aalstar" target="_blank">Okapi Aalstar</a> in 2012</span></li>
	<li>Hungarian Cup and Hungarian league championship with <a title="Szolnoki Olaj KK" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Szolnoki_Olaj_KK">Szolnoki Olaj</a> in 2014</li>
</ul>
He doesn't add 3-point shooting (career 28.8% from behind the arc), but he is very long and athletic and an outstanding defender with a 7'0.5" wingspan. He has been a very good shooter (44.0%) from 10-16 feet in his 1,062 NBA minutes, and he has picked up some defensive accolades along the way:
<ul>
	<li><span style="line-height: 13px;">2010 Pac-10 All-Defensive Team</span></li>
	<li>2013 D-League All-Defensive 2nd Team</li>
</ul>
Holiday was also named All-NBA D-League 3rd Team in 2013. That was his only full season in the D-League, and he had a pretty good season, averaging 17.3 points, 5.3 rebounds, 2.5 assists, a league-leading 2.4 steals and 1.2 blocks in 34.7 minutes. He also had an outstanding season from behind the arc, shooting 41.2% on 4.0 attempts per game - which gives hope that he can develop a 3-point shot in the NBA.

While this isn't the big deal Bulls fans were hoping for, at least the team gets more athletic and younger on the wing, and Holiday is signed through next season at the NBA minimum.

Here's a look at Holiday's highlights from his time with Golden State last season:

<iframe src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/Y8GrgMGk2yU" height="480" width="854" allowfullscreen="" frameborder="0"></iframe>

This video shows some of Holiday's D-League highlights from 2013:

<iframe src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/TVO9sOiVgGg" height="480" width="854" allowfullscreen="" frameborder="0"></iframe>

