<blockquote>
<p id="yui_3_18_1_1_1455805869775_2477">The Bulls have discussed deals with multiple NBA teams on Gasol, but one discussion lingered on Wednesday, league sources told The Vertical’s Wojnarowski and Chris Mannix: Gasol and <a id="yui_3_18_1_1_1455805869775_1755" href="https://sports.yahoo.com/nba/players/5190/" data-rapid_p="11">Tony Snell</a> to the <a href="https://sports.yahoo.com/nba/teams/sac/" data-rapid_p="12">Sacramento Kings</a> for <a href="https://sports.yahoo.com/nba/players/4485/" data-rapid_p="13">Kosta Koufos</a>, <a href="https://sports.yahoo.com/nba/players/5158/" data-rapid_p="14">Ben McLemore</a> and a lowering of <a id="yui_3_18_1_1_1455805869775_1680" href="https://sports.yahoo.com/news/guide-to-the-nba-trade-deadline--kings-020334169.html" target="_blank" data-rapid_p="15">the lottery protections on the 2016 first-round pick that Sacramento owes the Bulls</a>.</p>
<p id="yui_3_18_1_1_1455805869775_2577">The pick is protected Nos. 1-10, but the Bulls and Kings discussed lowering the protections further to give Chicago a better chance of obtaining use of the pick in 2016, league sources told The Vertical.</p>
<p id="yui_3_18_1_1_1455805869775_2582">The Kings reached out to the <a href="https://sports.yahoo.com/nba/teams/phi/" data-rapid_p="16">Philadelphia 76ers</a> on Wednesday, too, league sources said, because the Sixers have the right to swap picks with the Kings’ on the 2016 pick. The Kings wouldn’t be able to complete the deal involving the pick with Chicago unless they could reach an agreement with Philadelphia. The Sixers were preparing to ask for a further sweetener to allow the Kings to move on a deal with Chicago, league sources said.</p>
</blockquote>
It seems highly unlikely that the Sixers' pick would wind up below the Kings', barring the Kings' picking hitting in the lottery and winding up in the top-3. And I can't imagine the Kings lowering their protection with the Bulls to include a top-3 pick. But assuming the Kings pick is a better one, it seems as if the obvious solution would be for the Bulls to agree to continue to grant Philly the right to swap picks even after a Sacramento-Chicago trade.

[caption id="attachment_2264" align="alignleft" width="210"]<a href="http://www.chicagonow.com/bullsville/files/2016/02/SAC_McLemore_Ben.jpg"><img class=" wp-image-2264" alt="SAC_McLemore_Ben" src="http://www.chicagonow.com/bullsville/files/2016/02/SAC_McLemore_Ben-300x168.jpg" width="210" height="118" /></a> Ben McLemore[/caption]

That being said, the Kings are pretty desperate to make the playoffs this season, and a starting lineup featuring Rajon Rondo, Rudy Gay, DeMarcus Cousins and Gasol certainly looks pretty good on paper. That could possibly lead to the Kings removing all protection on their pick to entice the Bulls into making the trade, though I don't see any way it happens.

If it were to happen, this would be an outstanding return for the Bulls - McLemore has struggled in his 2 1/2 NBA seasons, but he is shooting a career-best 37.3% from behind the arc this season, and the Bulls definitely need to add shooters if they want to maximize Hoiberg's system.

Koufas is a good defender and a decent offensive player, and he has real center size at 7', 265. He doesn't have much range at all on his jumper, but he is a very effective scorer around the basket. He's also an outstanding offensive rebounder, averaging 4.0 offensive boards per 36 minutes with a 12.7% offensive rebound percentage for his career.

[caption id="attachment_2269" align="aligncenter" width="500"]<a href="http://www.chicagonow.com/bullsville/files/2016/02/SAC_Koufos_Kosta.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-2269" alt="Kosta Koufas" src="http://www.chicagonow.com/bullsville/files/2016/02/SAC_Koufos_Kosta.jpg" width="500" height="281" /></a> Kosta Koufas[/caption]

Koufas is also signed for two more seasons at very reasonable salaries of $8,046,500, $8,393,000 and $8,739,500 (the final year is a player option).

The only possible road block to this deal is an offer from Cleveland of Iman Shumpert (<a href="http://www.sacbee.com/sports/nba/sacramento-kings/kings-blog/article61001402.html" target="_blank">who the Kings are also interested in</a>) and Timofey Mozgov for McLemore and Koufas. Personally, I think the Kings would much rather have Gasol for their playoff push, but one never knows what is going on in Sacramento.

While 99.9% of NBA trade deadline rumors never come to fruition, it should be an interesting day for Bulls fans. There is always the possibility that the team makes a deal to dump just under $4.5 million in salary to get under the luxury tax threshold - but if they can pull off this Gasol deal, I'm sure they'd gladly pay the tax this season (Gasol and Snell for McLemore and Koufas actually adds almost $2 million to this season's payroll).";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:7;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:113:"
            
            
            
            
            
            
            
            
        ";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:3:{s:0:"";a:6:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:48:"NBA Trade Deadline: Bulls shopping Gasol, Gibson";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:92:"http://www.chicagonow.com/bullsville/2016/02/nba-trade-deadline-bulls-shopping-gasol-gibson/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:101:"http://www.chicagonow.com/bullsville/2016/02/nba-trade-deadline-bulls-shopping-gasol-gibson/#comments";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Wed, 17 Feb 2016 20:32:31 -0600";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:44:"http://www.chicagonow.com/bullsville/?p=2259";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:5359:"The NBA trade deadline is now less than 24 hours away, and while most Bulls fans seem to expect GarPax to pull off a deal where they bring back three times the value of what they send out, there are at least a few believable rumors out there.

According to Yahoo's <a href="http://sports.yahoo.com/news/nba-trade-deadline-buzz--clippers-move-closer-toward-channing-frye-deal-023959300.html" target="_blank">Adrian Wojnarowski</a>, the Bulls are looking to move All-Star center Pau Gasol:
<blockquote>
<p id="yui_3_18_1_1_1455758394086_1923">The <a id="yui_3_18_1_1_1455758394086_1925" href="http://sports.yahoo.com/nba/teams/chi/" data-rapid_p="17">Chicago Bulls</a> are aggressively shopping All-Star forward <a href="http://sports.yahoo.com/nba/players/3513/" data-rapid_p="18">Pau Gasol</a>, league sources told The Vertical.</p>
<p id="yui_3_18_1_1_1455758394086_1938">Gasol, 35, can opt out of his contract this summer and become an unrestricted free agent, and Bulls general manager Gar Forman seems determined to move him before Thursday's trade deadline with the hope of bringing back value.</p>
<p id="yui_3_18_1_1_1455758394086_1940">Gasol is expected to decline the player option on the $7.4 million owed him in 2016-17.</p>
<p id="yui_3_18_1_1_1455758394086_1942">Gasol is averaging 17 points and 10.9 rebounds for the struggling Bulls.</p>
</blockquote>
Honestly, I'm not sure there's a huge market out there for Gasol, and I haven't heard of a single rumor of any possible deals that might be out there.

<a href="https://twitter.com/thekapman/status/700025013907230720" target="_blank">David Kaplan did tweet</a> that the Bulls are looking for a player, not just a salary dump, which should be their approach. Moving Gasol would certainly seem to indicate that the Bulls are giving up on winning a championship (or even trying to beat Cleveland in the playoffs) this season, which might just be the right way of thinking with the way the team has played as of late.

However, that info is directly contradicted by the Tribune's <a href="https://twitter.com/KCJHoop/status/700020825173422081" target="_blank">KC Johnson, who tweeted</a> that the most likely scenario with Gasol is clearing salary to get under the luxury tax threshold - which makes sense in a season that is apparently going nowhere anyway. That being said, there's no reason the Bulls can't lower their payroll and get an asset in return for Gasol.

[caption id="attachment_995" align="aligncenter" width="529"]<a href="http://www.chicagonow.com/bullsville/files/2013/10/Taj-Gibson.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-995" alt="taj gibson bullsville" src="http://www.chicagonow.com/bullsville/files/2013/10/Taj-Gibson.jpg" width="529" height="599" /></a> Image courtesy of Bobak Ha'Eri[/caption]

Another rumor making the rounds has the Bulls offering up Taj Gibson to the Raptors in exchange for PF Patrick Patterson. <a href="http://espn.go.com/nba/story/_/id/14783975/the-nba-trade-deadline-full-big-names-cap-questions" target="_blank">Zach Lowe dropped this tidbit</a> in his weekly column on ESPN.com:
<blockquote>Chicago and Toronto had initial discussions on a Taj Gibson-Patrick Patterson swap that would give Chicago yet another stretch power forward and trim its tax bill, but those discussions appear to have led nowhere so far.</blockquote>
While most Bulls fans seem to hate this deal, I think it's a good one for the Bulls. As Lowe pointed out, it gives Hoiberg another stretch 4, it saves the Bulls about $2 million this year and $3 million next, and it makes the roster younger (Patterson is 26, Gibson 30).

<a href="http://www.chicagonow.com/bullsville/files/2016/02/SAC_McLemore_Ben.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-2264" alt="SAC_McLemore_Ben" src="http://www.chicagonow.com/bullsville/files/2016/02/SAC_McLemore_Ben.jpg" width="500" height="281" /></a>

Another rumor being floated by <a href="https://twitter.com/Chris_Broussard/status/700143160605937664" target="_blank">Chris Broussard</a> has the Bulls showing interest in Sacramento SG Ben McLemore. It's long been known that the Bulls were interested in McLemore on draft night in 2013, and <a href="http://espn.go.com/blog/marc-stein/post/_/id/4297/trade-chatter-is-kevin-love-untouchable" target="_blank">according to ESPN's Marc Stein</a> the Kings are said to be looking for immediate veteran help, so there might be a deal that could be worked out there.
<blockquote>Word is that the Kings, who are desperate to end a playoff drought spanning nine seasons and counting before moving into a new building next season, prefer immediate help in trade talks more than future picks.</blockquote>
Of course the Bulls have a vested interest in seeing the Kings make the playoffs, as this would mean that Sacramento would have to send their top-10 protected 1st-round draft pick to Chicago this summer. And adding McLemore, who is shooting over 37% from behind the arc this season, to the backcourt would be a huge bonus as well.

It should be an interesting evening and afternoon, as it seems like the Bulls might be actively involved in trade talks at the NBA trade deadline. Of course, I don't expect a deal to actually take place, but it's always fun to follow the rumors and hope the Bulls' front office can find a way to improve the team in February.";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:10:"Bullsville";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:5359:"The NBA trade deadline is now less than 24 hours away, and while most Bulls fans seem to expect GarPax to pull off a deal where they bring back three times the value of what they send out, there are at least a few believable rumors out there.

