        ";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:3:{s:0:"";a:6:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:59:"NBA Trade Deadline - Should the Bulls be buyers or sellers?";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:102:"http://www.chicagonow.com/bullsville/2016/02/nba-trade-deadline-should-the-bulls-be-buyers-or-sellers/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:111:"http://www.chicagonow.com/bullsville/2016/02/nba-trade-deadline-should-the-bulls-be-buyers-or-sellers/#comments";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Wed, 17 Feb 2016 00:25:34 -0600";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:44:"http://www.chicagonow.com/bullsville/?p=2249";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:2227:"The NBA trade deadline is almost upon us, and the $64,000 question that faces the Bulls' front office is a simple one - are they buyers, or are they sellers?

Or, as is the case almost annually, neither?

The Bulls have stood pat at the NBA trade deadline the last few seasons, and most fans expect them to do the same this season. Of course, this is because most fans expect them to completely fleece another team in a trade, which is of course completely unrealistic.

John Paxson and Gar Forman are constantly accused of overvaluing their assets, while fans consistently call out rumored deals as ridiculous while proposing deals of their own that actually DO overvalue Bulls' players:

(From the busiest Bulls' fan forum on the internet):
<blockquote>In the circumstance we did trade Jimmy (Butler), I can think of 2 trade partners that would make more sense - Milwaukee and Portland. I would prefer (Khris) Middleton + (Jabari) Parker+ (draft) picks or (CJ) McCollum + (Noah) Vonleh + (Allen) Crabbe + pick to (Victor Oladipo) + (Nikola Vucevic) + pick.</blockquote>
Really?

Who wouldn't?

If you need reminding, Middleton is a 6'8" shooting guard who is giving the Bucks 18/4/4 this year while shooting 40.5% from behind the arc and playing pretty good defense. Parker is a year removed from being the #2 overall pick in the 2014 draft. AND this guy expects the Bucks to throw in a draft pick??

McCollum is a 6'4" shooting guard who is averaging almost 21 points per game on 39.2% 3-point shooting in his 3rd NBA season. Crabbe is a 6'6" shooting guard who averages over 11 points/game in his 3rd year, while Vonleh is a 6'10" power forward who is only 20 years old and less than two years removed from being a top-10 draft pick.

In addition to trading Butler for one of these packages, maybe they can trade Kirk Hinrich and Mike Dunleavy for Kevin Durant and Russell Westbrook? Surely they can move Taj Gibson and Aaron Brooks for LeBron James and Kyrie Irving?

I've tried to look at the Bulls' NBA trade deadline options from a comical point of view tonight, tomorrow I'll look at what deals the Bulls might actually have a chance of pulling off before Thursday afternoon rolls around.

